The paper deals with data visualization and clustering techniques for discovering discriminative structures in high-dimensional data, specifically in the context of image splicing localization. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of machine learning techniques such as stochastic gradient descent and backpropagation, which suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also deals with multimedia (cs.MM) data, which further supports the possibility of it belonging to the cs.CV sub-category. The paper also mentions the problem of image forgery, which suggests that it may belong to the computer security and cryptography (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with information retrieval (cs.IR) in the sense that it aims to extract relevant features from high-dimensional data.
